  "prompt": "What are schedules in the Indian constitution?",
  "response": "In the Indian Constitution, schedules are specific parts of the document that contain detailed provisions, lists, and arrangements related to various aspects of governance, power distribution, and administrative matters. Here are the key details about schedules:\n\n1. Number of Schedules:\n- There are currently 12 schedules in the Indian Constitution\n- Each schedule deals with a specific subject or provides detailed information about certain constitutional provisions\n\n2. Important Schedules:\n\na) First Schedule:\n- Lists all states and union territories of India\n- Describes the territorial boundaries of states\n\nb) Fifth Schedule:\n- Deals with administration of Scheduled Areas and Tribal Areas\n- Provides special provisions for protecting tribal rights and interests\n\nc) Sixth Schedule:\n- Contains provisions for autonomous district councils in northeastern states\n- Provides special administrative arrangements for tribal areas\n\nd) Seventh Schedule:\n- Defines the distribution of legislative powers between Union and State governments\n- Contains three lists: Union List, State List, and Concurrent List\n\ne) Eighth Schedule:\n- Lists officially recognized languages in India\n- Currently includes 22 languages\n\nf) Ninth Schedule:\n- Contains laws related to land reforms and abolition of zamindari system\n- Protects certain laws from judicial review\n\nThese schedules play a crucial role in defining the constitutional framework and governance structure of India.",
